transcript.message: Peggy, she said, you want to buy it? Well, there she was. There we were. She sold the car, which was the BMW that she had bought in Schiphol a couple of years earlier, which I drove across Europe with her. She sold the car at the border. We had all of our baggage and pistachio nuts, of course. And so the fellow took us to a place called Piazza del Vecchio where he had bought some things for us to go to a hotel which was across the way from the train station. And the next morning we went over and got on the train and we were driving. We were driving down that street, it was like 10 miles away from Munich because that's where my friend had ordered a BMW from the factory. So I was like, oh, this is really cool. And then I saw this guy who had a BMW in his car and he was driving around and he said, hey, you know what? You can't drive around here. You have to drive around here. And so we drove around the city of Munich and we were driving around the city of Munich because that's where my friend had ordered a BMW from the factory or from a dealer there. And so that's why she sold the car at the border. And on the train there was a fellow in the cabin with us who spoke to us and said that he was a prisoner of war in the United States during the Second World War and how well he was treated as a prisoner of war and was evidently very happy to be a prisoner of war rather than on the line. So that was interesting and I don't remember where he was a prisoner of war in which country, in which city in this area of the United States. Anyway, we were in some restaurant in Germany and I remember ordering a baked potato and I asked the fellow if he had sour cream and he kind of scolded me, he said you're not in America, you know, he said no we don't have sour cream. So I was like okay. And then my friend came over to the restaurant and she told me that they had a really good one called the American Sour Cream with Baked Potatoes but he hadn't really tried it. So I was like, well, you know what? I'm gonna try it. And so we went to this restaurant and we were having a really good time. And then my friend came over to the restaurant and she said, I wouldn't let my mother take the purse home. I put it in the vice for basket along with my gold coins that my friend Peggy had given me, two of them. They had slipped through the lining and I remember when I got back to the States that there was a hole in the lining and I thought, since I didn't see the coins, I thought they were in my suitcase, but they weren't. And my mother said, see, if you had let me bring that purse home, you would have had your coins. Anyway, my mother flew out, I went on, we went on to, we did some touring in Vienna and eventually ended up in the south of Spain with some other friends. One of my friends lived there. These were friends from my Iranian days and visited with them. And then my friend, oh, we had picked up the car, the BMW in Munich and drove to Germany. And he was driving around in his car with a friend of mine who was also a friend of mine. And that's what we were driving then. My friend decided that she wanted to fly back to the States and leave me with the car. She'd come back to Europe and we could go traveling a bit. So she flew off to the States, left me with the car and my other friend Gwen, and Gwen and I traveled. We have remembered driving around Germany, around Paris, and we went to Versailles. People were so nice helping us with directions, how to get here to there. Anyway I decided that I'd had enough of traveling, Gwen decided she was taking a job in Doha, somewhere in the Middle East. She was going to fly home. So I left the car at the Schiphol Airport, long-term parking, I left the BMW there, took my car keys, took the car keys home with me, flew out of Amsterdam. And then we went back to London and we were in London for about a week or two. And then we got back to London and we were in London for about a week or two. And then we got back to London for about a week or two. And flew on to the States, contacted Peggy sent her the car keys and I stayed in the United States Center for a couple of years so.
